  }
}
```

It:

 1. Allows building of objects including fields of the parent
 2. Serializes/Deserializes with the default `ObjectMapper` and Jackson
 3. Instances of the parent and children classes are immutable

My advice against other examples:

1. Try not to put custom annotations on particular classes, it makes it _inhomogeneous_. Any way, you will come to a generic solution one day.
2. Try not to put `Jackson` annotations on any fields on constructors, it creates coupling, when Jackson is capable to serialize/deserialize without any annotations.
3. Do not use `@AllArgsConstructor` for immutable entities. When your class has only **final** fields, conceptually right is `@RequiredArgsConstructor`, that&#39;s how you guarantee that class-clients always will rely only on a constructor with the immutable entity. Will `@AllArgsConstructor` it might lead to passing nulls.

